I don't think it's as simple as that. On my system, SVG files are of the correct type:

```
$ xdg-mime query filetype archlinux-symbolic.svg
image/svg+xml
```

Moreover, I have explicitly added this mimetype to the list at the end of `image.js`:

```
var mimeTypes = ['image/svg+xml'];
let formats = GdkPixbuf.Pixbuf.get_formats();
for (let idx in formats)
    mimeTypes = mimeTypes.concat(formats[idx].get_mime_types());
```

This still doesn't work, although when I remove `text.js` from `org.gnome.NautilusPreviewer.src.gresource.xml`, the SVG file is correctly being previewed.

It seems that the MIME handler is giving the text viewer priority. Inspecting `mimeHandler.js` a little more closely, it seems that the SVG file is being recognised as a child type of `text/plain` before the membership of `image/svg+xml' gets a chance to be checked against the image handler. This is definitely something that can be fixed in Sushi. This can e.g. be done by checking all viewers for explicit membership before falling back to parent types, like so:

```
    let renderer = renderers.find((r) => {
        // first, try a direct match with the mimetype itself
        if (r.mimeTypes.includes(mime))
            return true;
        return false;
    });

    if (!renderer){
        renderer = renderers.find((r) => {
            // if this fails, try to see if we have any handlers
            // registered for a parent type
            if (r.mimeTypes.some((rm) => Gio.content_type_is_a(mime, rm)))
                return true;
            return false;
        });
    }
```

Modifing `mimeHandler.js` in this manner fixes the issue for me.

